ce:section.ce:para:
The nanostructure morphology and particle sizes of as-prepared CQDs were characterized by capturing transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images. Spherical nanoparticles were uniformly distributed and well separated from each other without obvious aggregation (Fig. 1
                        a–c). The average particle sizes of b-, g-, and o-CQDs were 3.31, 3.56, and 3.38 nm (statistical particle number>50), respectively, and particle size distribution roughly meet Gaussian, as shown in Fig. 1d–f. In addition, the XRD pattern of CQDs (Fig. 1g) showed two broad peaks roughly centered at 10° and 25°, corresponding to the characteristic (001) peak of graphene oxide and the broad (002) peak of graphene, respectively, which was consistent with reported results in literature [29,30]. The particle sizes of b-, g-, and o-CQDs were similar, so the difference in their luminescence mainly originated from surface functional groups. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) and fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) spectra are effective means to explore the diverse surface functional groups of CQDs. XPS showed O contents of 10.72%, 14.1%, and 24.19% in b-, g-, and o-CQDs, while the corresponding C contents were 86.34%, 83.44%, and 72.38% (Fig. 1j, Fig. S1 and Table S1, in the Supporting Information), respectively, indicating that the redshift of PL peaks was mainly caused by the increase of oxidation degree rather than CC conjugate domain [31]. Both g- and o-CQDs showed O–H bond stretching vibration peaks at 3200-3400 cm−1 in their FTIR spectra (Fig. 1h) [32], while the obvious C–O–C peaks only appeared in high resolution XPS O 1s spectrum of o-CQDs (Fig. 1m), which further supported the above view. The Cl contents of tricolor CQDs detected by XPS were 0.16%, 0.58%, and 0.48%, respectively, and the stretching vibration peaks of C–Cl appeared at 669 and 768 cm−1 in FTIR spectra [33]. Additionally, strong stretching vibration peaks of C–H appeared at 2850 and 2920 cm−1 in the FTIR spectra of tricolor CQDs [34], indicating that CHCl3 participated in solvent-thermal reaction and became components of CQDs. Furthermore, the FWHM of b-CQDs was only 8 nm (Fig. 1i), the narrowest one to our knowledge, and is even comparable to those of colloidal semiconductor quantum dots and rare earth complexes (see Table 1
                        ). Although the raw material also has fluorescence, the synthesized CQDs showed different luminescence from the raw material (Fig. S2). After the reaction was complete, the raw materials not involved in reaction were removed by dialysis (see Supporting Information for detail), so as not to interfere with the experimental results. In b-CQDs, the stretching vibration peak of CC/CN at 1640 cm−1 was observed, meanwhile, the contents of CC and pyrrole N were comparatively high according to high resolution XPS (Fig. 1k and l). High contents of CC and pyrrole N, as well as the lack of O-containing functional groups on the surface of b-CQDs increase electron cloud density and the degree of electron delocalization, thus cause the small fluctuations in energy bands and the reduced FWHM of emission, which have been proved by computational chemistry in previously reported works [3,35,36]. In summary, the feasible method to reduce the FWHM contains expanding efficient conjugated domains, and reducing electron-withdrawing groups [18], for example, choosing molecular precursors with large aromatic π structures [16], or selecting solvents [37,38] and reaction temperature [39] that can promote the dehydration and carbonization process of precursors.
